WEBVTT

1
00:00.480 --> 00:08.080
The samplebased quantum diagonalization method or SQD for short is a quantum classical hybrid algorithm like Kryov

2
00:08.080 --> 00:14.080
quantum diagonalization KQD like VQE and many others. In using such hybrid

3
00:14.080 --> 00:22.720
algorithms, it may be useful to think about where each algorithm leverages quantum and classical computing. Recall that VQE creates states on a quantum

4
00:22.720 --> 00:28.720
circuit using classically optimized parameters. In that case, the state itself is on a quantum computer. Though

5
00:28.720 --> 00:34.160
obtaining the target state is a process that combines both classical and quantum computing.

6
00:34.160 --> 00:38.559
The expectation value of the operator is calculated using quantum measurements.

7
00:38.559 --> 00:42.719
But some classical combining of terms is also necessary.

8
00:42.719 --> 00:50.399
In contrast, SQD uses a quantum computer to generate a useful subspace onto which the Hamiltonian or other operator can be

9
00:50.399 --> 00:58.000
projected. The Hamiltonian is then diagonalized entirely classically to find the target state. Suppose we have a

10
00:58.000 --> 01:04.400
problem of interest to science or industry that can be cast as an igen solver problem on a matrix of n rows and

11
01:04.400 --> 01:12.880
n columns. Suppose further that n is large enough that exact classical diagonalization is not an option. It

12
01:12.880 --> 01:20.960
would clearly be advantageous to reduce the dimensions of our matrix while preserving all the relevant features of the ground state. Indeed, that is the

13
01:20.960 --> 01:28.720
goal of many approximate igen solver approaches, including classical kryoff methods. Let's assume that we know enough about our problem to make a

14
01:28.720 --> 01:34.960
reasonably good guess about the form of the ground state, but not enough to solve the problem outright. In that

15
01:34.960 --> 01:41.439
case, we could make many measurements of our fair approximation of the target ground state. The results of these

16
01:41.439 --> 01:48.720
measurements give us a subspace of computational basis states that contain all the relevant components of our

17
01:48.720 --> 01:56.880
ground state. Projecting onto that subspace would yield a smaller matrix that still contains the relevant degrees

18
01:56.880 --> 02:03.680
of freedom. The workflow for this is as follows. You start by choosing a good

19
02:03.680 --> 02:12.239
onzot. More precisely, choose an anzot whose support coincides with that of the target state. We'll discuss exactly what

20
02:12.239 --> 02:19.920
that means. Next, measure the state in the computational basis as is done with the sampler primitive.

21
02:19.920 --> 02:27.200
Then, use the results of the sampling to define a subspace that contains the ground state.

22
02:27.200 --> 02:36.000
Then, project your matrix onto that subspace. Finally, diagonalize the smaller projected matrix classically.

23
02:36.000 --> 02:42.319
Let's pick apart each of these steps, paying special attention to defining the subspace.

24
02:42.319 --> 02:49.599
Throughout all of quantum computing, choosing a goods is always critical. In the case of SQD, your choice of ANSOT

25
02:49.599 --> 02:54.959
will determine what computational basis states may be measured in the sampling.

26
02:54.959 --> 03:02.640
The true ground state can be expressed as a superposition of some subset of computational basis states. That subset

27
03:02.640 --> 03:10.159
is called the support of the ground state. To get a good estimate of your ground state and its energy, your anzots

28
03:10.159 --> 03:17.360
must have a non-zero projection onto the computational basis states in the support of the ground state.

29
03:17.360 --> 03:24.239
This diagram represents the space spanned by all possible states on the number of cubits being used. We want an

30
03:24.239 --> 03:30.319
un anzot with support that contains the support of the true ground state.

31
03:30.319 --> 03:36.640
Consider a very small example system with a ground state of s ground is8 *

32
03:36.640 --> 03:41.599
the state 1 0 0 plus 6 * the state 001.

33
03:41.599 --> 03:52.720
This has support made of those two vectors 1 0 0 and 0 1. Let's say the Anzots is of the form SNZOT 1 is A times

34
03:52.720 --> 04:01.040
the state 1 0 0 plus B * the state 0 1 0 plus C * the state 001. So that its

35
04:01.040 --> 04:08.239
support is the set of three vectors 1 0 0 1 0 and 0 0 1 a superset of the

36
04:08.239 --> 04:13.599
support of the ground state. This is a good anzot.

37
04:13.599 --> 04:20.880
Now imagine that we had instead chosen an anzot of the form szots 2 is a * the

38
04:20.880 --> 04:25.600
state 1 1 0 plus b * the state 011.

39
04:25.600 --> 04:32.960
This has support made of those two vectors 11 1 0 and 011 which has no overlap with the support of the ground

40
04:32.960 --> 04:37.280
state. This is a bad anzot.

41
04:37.280 --> 04:44.560
Note that we do not necessarily require that the unzots be a good approximation of the ground state. The unzots could

42
04:44.560 --> 04:52.560
have much larger support or the coefficients could be very different on the anzots and the true ground state and still work well.

43
04:52.560 --> 05:00.320
At this stage, we've used a well- motivated to make the quantum computer adopt the state similar to our target

44
05:00.320 --> 05:08.720
state. Shown here is the unitary coupled gastro or UCJ unzots which is very useful in quantum chemistry.

45
05:08.720 --> 05:15.360
We now want to measure the state of the system obtaining bitst strings describing the collapsed state of each

46
05:15.360 --> 05:22.880
cubit. Recall that Hamiltonian estimation as in VQE requires many quantum measurements. This is partly to

47
05:22.880 --> 05:29.680
reduce uncertainty and partly due to the number of groups of commuting Paul that make up the Hamiltonian.

48
05:29.680 --> 05:37.759
In sampling methods, you still need lots of measurements, but the reasons are different. Now, we need many measurements to effectively sample the

49
05:37.759 --> 05:45.520
many computational basis states involved in highly entangled quantum states. In SQD, the sampled bitstrings correspond

50
05:45.520 --> 05:52.720
to configurations of the simulated system. If the system being studied is subject to absolute constraints like

51
05:52.720 --> 05:59.680
conservation laws in physics or chemistry, then most of the measured states will be valid. But some sampled

52
05:59.680 --> 06:07.840
bitst strings correspond to invalid or non-physical configurations due to noise and errors. A process called

53
06:07.840 --> 06:15.039
configuration recovery aims to refine these noisy samples into a set of more accurate configurations.

54
06:15.039 --> 06:22.560
This process involves generating new configurations by probabilistically flipping individual bits based on

55
06:22.560 --> 06:27.039
averaged orbital occupancies and known particle numbers.

56
06:27.039 --> 06:34.000
The refined configurations are then used to span subspaces for Hamiltonian projection and diagonalization,

57
06:34.000 --> 06:38.880
iteratively improving the fidelity of the quantum state representation.

58
06:38.880 --> 06:45.360
Let's look at a trivially small example of configuration recovery to understand its meaning. Suppose we measure a

59
06:45.360 --> 06:52.560
quantum system with four cubits representing four molecular orbitals and obtain the following bitstrings from the

60
06:52.560 --> 07:00.080
quantum processor. Each bitst string represents the occupancy of an orbital. One for

61
07:00.080 --> 07:08.240
occupied, zero for unoccupied. Kiskit uses a notation in which the least significant cubit is on the far right.

62
07:08.240 --> 07:15.199
For example, 1 0 1 0 indicates that orbitals 1 and three are occupied. These

63
07:15.199 --> 07:23.039
measurements have been chosen for pedagogical reasons only. The resulting occupancies may not match a physical system. In physical contexts, it is

64
07:23.039 --> 07:29.919
often the case that the system has a known total number of particles. There also may be other conservation laws that

65
07:29.919 --> 07:36.240
you can leverage to determine the physicality of a measured state. To stay concrete, let's assume our system is

66
07:36.240 --> 07:44.240
known to have a total particle number of n= 2. This tells us the total number of ones that should appear in our state

67
07:44.240 --> 07:47.840
label, which is called a Hamming weight constraint.

68
07:47.840 --> 07:56.400
However, some measured configurations violate this constraint. The state 1 0 1 0 is physically valid. But the state 1 1

69
07:56.400 --> 08:02.400
1 0 has too many particles and the state of all zeros has too few particles. Zero

70
08:02.400 --> 08:09.520
in fact. These violations can be due to noise in the system or errors in measurement. We need a way to get back

71
08:09.520 --> 08:15.280
to configurations that make physical sense at least in an approximate way.

72
08:15.280 --> 08:18.319
This is called configuration recovery.

73
08:18.319 --> 08:25.599
To correct our noisy samples, we probabilistically flip bits in invalid configurations based on the average

74
08:25.599 --> 08:30.240
orbital occupancy averaged over valid configurations.

75
08:30.240 --> 08:38.479
Orbital occupancies are the expectation values of the number operator acting on each orbital. This is estimated and

76
08:38.479 --> 08:46.959
refined self-consistently using the states produced from SQD. Let's look at orbital 2 for example. In two of the

77
08:46.959 --> 08:55.360
four valid configurations, orbital 2 was occupied. This gives us an expected occupancy of 0.5.

78
08:55.360 --> 09:05.120
We do the same for the other three orbitals. Now we return to an invalid configuration 1 1 0. We can flip one of

79
09:05.120 --> 09:12.160
the bits from 1 to zero to generate a valid configuration. But which one should we flip? One way of deciding is

80
09:12.160 --> 09:18.399
through the deviation of each orbital's occupancy from the averages we just calculated.

81
09:18.399 --> 09:25.279
Here we see that the biggest difference is in the occupation of orbital one. So we might expect that bit one should be

82
09:25.279 --> 09:32.880
flipped from a one to a zero. Of course, orbital 2 is not far behind. And it's always possible, however unlikely, that

83
09:32.880 --> 09:37.680
this measured state is the result of multiple errors on the same state.

84
09:37.680 --> 09:45.200
Choosing only the largest deviation from mean for all invalid states is not optimal. Instead, bits are flipped

85
09:45.200 --> 09:51.920
probabilistically with the probability being a function of the differences shown here. Let us suppose that in this

86
09:51.920 --> 10:02.160
case we do change the bit that differs the most from the average occupation. So 1 1 0 becomes 1 1 0 0. We would do the

87
10:02.160 --> 10:10.560
same process for the other invalid choice. Let's say that in this case we end up flipping bits one and three.

88
10:10.560 --> 10:17.200
After this correction process, we have a new set of configurations that might look like this.

89
10:17.200 --> 10:24.240
Using this refined set, we can update the average orbital occupancy to improve fidelity. In our case, the new

90
10:24.240 --> 10:28.320
occupancies are these.

91
10:28.320 --> 10:34.880
This iterative recovery process ensures that noisy measurements are filtered into physically meaningful

92
10:34.880 --> 10:43.040
configurations, improving the accuracy of igen state approximations in SQD. The SQD Kiskit add-on has some tools that

93
10:43.040 --> 10:49.279
will be instrumental in this process. If we've done a good job sampling the states in the support of the true ground

94
10:49.279 --> 10:56.160
state of the system, then we should be able to look at only the parts of the Hamiltonian that act on this subspace

95
10:56.160 --> 11:05.200
and still obtain a good ground state and energy. In our trivially small 4 cubit example, there are initially 2 or 16

96
11:05.200 --> 11:11.760
possible states of the system. Using a combination of sampling and configuration recovery, we reduce this

97
11:11.760 --> 11:18.880
to three states in our subspace of interest. three states that we hope make up the support of the true ground state.

98
11:18.880 --> 11:27.600
We now project our full Hamiltonian onto that subspace. That is we make a matrix M out of a column of vectors from our

99
11:27.600 --> 11:37.440
recovered sampled subspace and an analogous one M dagger out of the rows and we multiply M dagger HM

100
11:37.440 --> 11:43.680
pictorially. This means taking the matrix elements in the rows and columns corresponding to the states in our

101
11:43.680 --> 11:50.959
recovered sampled subspace. The highlighted rows and columns are those corresponding to our subspace. And the

102
11:50.959 --> 11:58.079
darker highlighted boxes where they overlap are the elements that we keep for our new projected matrix.

103
11:58.079 --> 12:04.240
Now that we have selected out the subspace of interest, we can diagonalize this matrix on a classical computer

104
12:04.240 --> 12:11.760
using a standard solver. If the true ground state is comprised entirely of states in our subspace, this

105
12:11.760 --> 12:18.639
diagonalization should yield the correct ground state and ground state energy. If we merely have most of the ground state

106
12:18.639 --> 12:25.360
support, we may get close. Once we've obtained the ground state for this projected Hamiltonian, we have a very

107
12:25.360 --> 12:30.560
useful state from which to calculate the average occupancy of each orbital.

108
12:30.560 --> 12:37.200
Previously, our occupancies were calculated from states that we sampled using an anzots that we hoped would help

109
12:37.200 --> 12:45.440
us approach our ground state. But there was no guarantee that the average occupancy of each orbital from that sampling corresponded to the occupancy

110
12:45.440 --> 12:53.839
in the lowest energy state. Let's back up. We had a sampling of computational states. We used configuration recovery

111
12:53.839 --> 13:02.000
to correct any that were physically invalid. Then we calculated the average orbital occupancy using all of them. The

112
13:02.000 --> 13:09.440
ground state might only include some of them. The ground state of this projected Hamiltonian may not be the true ground

113
13:09.440 --> 13:15.920
state of our original system, but it is the lowest energy state that can be created using any superposition of the

114
13:15.920 --> 13:23.920
recovered states in our subspace. The orbital occupancy of this state will yield an energy less than or equal to

115
13:23.920 --> 13:31.839
the energy of the occupancy obtained from the recovered space. So this occupancy is a better estimate of our

116
13:31.839 --> 13:39.600
ground state occupancy. We can repeat the configuration recovery process using this new occupancy and we can iterate

117
13:39.600 --> 13:45.920
this until our convergence criteria are met. Sample-based quantum diagonalization is fast compared to

118
13:45.920 --> 13:53.519
other near-term algorithms like VQE. It's more scalable and it is robust to noise and errors in sampling. It does

119
13:53.519 --> 14:01.680
still require that we prepare a good onsance with a large projection under the support of the true ground state of our system. If nothing at all is known

120
14:01.680 --> 14:08.000
about our true ground state, SQD may need to be used in conjunction with other methods to first learn about the

121
14:08.000 --> 14:11.199
ground state and iteratively approach it.

122
14:11.199 --> 14:17.199
SQD plays a critical role in the emerging suite of classical quantum hybrid algorithms and is one of the

123
14:17.199 --> 14:22.519
greatest drivers toward useful quantum computing.
